In [10]:
#vocab_size = 10000   only a reminder for the value of params.
#max_length = 100
embedding_dim = 16
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Embedding, Dense
model = tf.keras.Sequential([
    # the embedding . where the direction of each word will be learned epoch by epoch.
    tf.keras.layers.Embedding(vocab_size, embedding_dim, input_length=max_length),
    # adding up the vectors like i told you before. but also do an avrage
    tf.keras.layers.GlobalAveragePooling1D(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(24, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy',optimizer='adam',metrics=['accuracy'])

about "Dense" layer.

chatGPT say :

The Dense layer in this code is a fully-connected layer. It takes in an input tensor and applies a linear transformation to it, followed by an activation function. The Dense layer in this code has 24 units and the activation function used is the relu (Rectified Linear Activation). This means that the output of each unit in the Dense layer will be the input value if it is positive, and 0 if it is negative. The Dense layer with 1 unit and the sigmoid activation function at the end is used for binary classification. The output of this layer will be a probability value between 0 and 1, indicating the probability that the input data belongs to the positive class.

and about model.compile():

model.compile() is used to configure the learning process of the model. It takes three important arguments:

  1. loss: It specifies the loss function that should be used to calculate the error between the predicted output and the true output. In this case, the binary_crossentropy loss is used for binary classification.

  2. optimizer: It specifies the optimizer that should be used to minimize the loss. In this case, the adam optimizer is used. It is a gradient-based optimization algorithm that is generally used in deep learning models.

  3. metrics: It specifies the metrics that should be used to evaluate the model. In this case, the accuracy metric is used to calculate the accuracy of the model on the training and validation sets.

Together, these three arguments define the learning process of the model. The model will use the specified loss function and optimizer to learn the weights and biases of the model, and the specified metrics will be used to evaluate the model's performance on the training and validation sets.

until now .. what we have seen?

we saw how to tokenize text and how to use sequences of tokens, to train a neural network. in particular we saw how to classifed text by sentiments.

now we gonna talk about genetating test . this part including RNN.

until now the order of the words didnt matter. what determind the sentiment was the vector that resulted in adding up all of the individual vectors for the endividual words.

the direction of that vector roughly gave us the sentiments.

but it we're going to generate text , the order does matter !

for an example.. "today the weather is gorgeous and i see a beatiful blue .." if we want to predict the next word , and the concept of creating text really boils down to predicting the next word , you are probably say, "sky" becuse that comes after "beatiful" and "blue" and the context is the "weather"

Because of using RNN

Think for a moment. Fibonacci series. remember that ? It creates a sequence based on the first numbers. For example: 1,2,3,5,8,13.. If we look at the first number.. It is as if it is contained in numbers that have been calculated ahead.

Actually... the number 5 for example is calculated by the 2 preceding it, 2+3.

But 3 is calculated from 1+2

So actually you can imagine that 1,2 are words! that in fact their content .. thinks further in the chain and actually considered his existence. that 1 still continues to exist throughout the series.

so how we gonna do that ?

LSTM.

from now on there is a few models that can train the model .

in task 4 i will show how it is done .

    # 
    tf.keras.layers.Embedding(tokenizer.vocab_size,64),
    # "tf.keras.layers.LSTM(64)" takes a numeric parameter for the number of hidden nodes within it.
    #and this is also the dimensionality of the output space from this layer.
    # Bidirectional : if you want to be bi-directional , we can wrap this layer in a bi-directional like this,and you are good to go.
    # remember that this will look at your sentence forward and backward ! 
    #learn the best for each params for each and then merge them.
    tf.keras.layers.Bidirectional(tf.keras.layers.LSTM(64)),

    tf.keras.layers.Bidirectional(tf.keras.layers.LSTM(64,return_sequences=True)),
    tf.keras.layers.Bidirectional(tf.keras.layers.LSTM(32)),

MY_EXTRA_SYMBOLS = util.EXTRA_SYMBOLS
"""
load_words function in util : 

Reading text until some limit we choose.
x:
split lines until "\n"
its gonna be our x

i2w:
finding the max len of x (make sure the line is not up then what we passed into the function to be, maybe some one want our sequences to be short)
now tokenizer them.
Creating the vocabulary set of tokens with the most common words (saving place for EXTRA_SYMBOLS)
Creating an array of words from the vocabulary set and adding the EXTRA_SYMBOLS to the start.
it contains array as index-to-word dictionary and its value is i2w

w2i:
now we make an array of words from the indexs of the words.. like the "word_index = tokenizer.word_index"
that tokened and indexed will be in value w2i , but only the words in the order of the indexs.

what we got  ?
x - was : our sequences per line
x - now : our index per each word at each line ,like a transalte
i2w - array as index-to-word dictionary
w2i - an ordered array with the words for each index in our history of words collected.
    
The "source" parameter is a string that represents the file path to the text file that the function reads from.

The "vocab_size" parameter controls the maximum number of !! unique !! words that the function retains from the text file.
If there are more unique words than this, the function only keeps the "vocab_size" most frequent words and replaces the rest with the special token "<UNK>".

The "limit" parameter is an optional parameter that allows you to limit the number of characters read from the text file.
 This is useful when you are working with large corpora and want to limit the amount of data loaded for testing or debugging purposes.

The "max_length" parameter is an optional parameter that allows you to limit the maximum number of words in each sentence.
If the sentence has more words than the max_length, this sentence is removed..
"""

def load_wordsPractice(source, vocab_size=10000, limit=None, max_length=None):
    x_data = source
    print('raw data read')

    if limit is not None:
        x_data = x_data[:limit]
                                          # x_data.lower().split to change ! 
    x = [text_to_word_sequence(x) for x in x_data.lower().split('\n') if len(x) > 0]
    
    if max_length is not None:
        x = [s for s in x if len(s) <= max_length]

    dist = FreqDist(np.hstack(x))
    x_vocab = dist.most_common(vocab_size - len(MY_EXTRA_SYMBOLS))
    i2w = [word[0] for word in x_vocab]
    i2w = MY_EXTRA_SYMBOLS + i2w
    w2i = {word:ix for ix, word in enumerate(i2w)}
    for i, sentence in enumerate(x):
        for j, word in enumerate(sentence):
            if word in w2i:
                x[i][j] = w2i[word]
            else:
                x[i][j] = w2i['<UNK>']

    return x, w2i, i2w

x_data = "i love my dog,my dog have a name,my name is dori,dori are a man,dori is not a dog"

x, w2i, i2w = load_wordsPractice(x_data,vocab_size = 20)

def to_categoricalPractice(batch, num_classes):
    """
"num_classes" refer to the total number of unique words in the vocabulary
for each sequences that represent in a list.
the easy way to say it .. it the num of column / len of the list
or how much i want it to be ! maybe i want any list to have extra 1 place to be zero also..
"""
    b, l = batch.shape
    out = np.zeros((b, l, num_classes))
    for i in range(b):
        seq = batch[0, :]
        out[i, :, :] = keras.utils.to_categorical(seq, num_classes=num_classes)

    return out

def interpolate(start, end, steps):
#This is a common interpolation technique and is useful in many machine learning, computer vision,
#and other data science applications. The most common use case of this function is using it to generate data,
#where the start and end could be real data points and the steps are the number of data points you want to generate between the start and end
    result = np.zeros((steps+2, start.shape[0]))
    for i, d in enumerate(np.linspace(0,1, steps+2)):
        result[i, :] = start * (1-d) + end * d

    return result
from scipy.special import logsumexp

from collections import defaultdict, Counter, OrderedDict

def sample_logitsPractice(preds, temperature=1.0):
    """
    Sample an index from a logit vector.

    :param preds:
    :param temperature:
    :return:
    """
    preds = np.asarray(preds).astype('float64')

    if temperature == 0.0:
        return np.argmax(preds)
# the divied is done to ensure that the resulting array of probabilities sum to 1 (This is called the softmax operation).
    preds = preds / temperature
    preds = preds - logsumexp(preds)
#randomly choose an index from the preds array, with the probabilities of each index
# its happing becuse if we just take each time the highest value .. we can get the same asnwer again and again ! 
# like we talked in class. the word "and" is very very common. 
#and becuse of that we dont want the word to be always the currect choice !
    
    
    #param 1 :from which to choose an item,
    #param 2 :the number of items to choose
    #param 3:list of float probabilities which define the likelihood of each item being chosen.
    
    choice = np.random.choice(len(preds), 1, p=np.exp(preds))

    return choice

# This function is used to convert a list of sentence represented by a list of indexes to a list of sentences represented by a list of words.
class OrderedCounter(Counter, OrderedDict):
    'Counter that remembers the order elements are first encountered'

    def __repr__(self):
        return '%s(%r)' % (self.__class__.__name__, OrderedDict(self))

    def __reduce__(self):
        return self.__class__, (OrderedDict(self),)

def idx2word(idx, i2w, pad_idx):

    sent_str = [str()]*len(idx)

    for i, sent in enumerate(idx):

        for word_id in sent:

            if word_id == pad_idx:
                break
            sent_str[i] += i2w[str(word_id.item())] + " "

        sent_str[i] = sent_str[i].strip()


    return sent_str

def parsing_loss(y_true, y_pred):
    return K.sparse_categorical_crossentropy(y_true, y_pred, from_logits=True)

def perplexity(y_true, y_pred):
    loss = parsing_loss(y_true, y_pred)
    perplexity = K.exp(loss)
    return perplexity

In general, bidirectional layers are more powerful than reversing the input sequence with the go_backwards parameter. Because bidirectional layers process the input sequence in two different directions and combine the information from both, they can capture more meaningful patterns in the data and provide more accurate predictions.

def My_Sequential(How_To_Name_It,doBackwards=False,doBidirectional=False):
  if((doBackwards == True) and (doBidirectional == True)):
    print("we want only 1 choise of back learner")
    return 
  input = Input(shape=(None, ))
  embedding = Embedding(numwords, options.embedding_size, input_length=None)
  embedded = embedding(input)
  
  if(doBidirectional == True):
    decoder_lstm = Bidirectional(LSTM(options.lstm_capacity, return_sequences=True))
    h = decoder_lstm(embedded)
    if options.extra is not None:
      for _ in range(options.extra):
        h = Bidirectional(LSTM(options.lstm_capacity, return_sequences=True))(h)
  else:
    decoder_lstm = LSTM(options.lstm_capacity, return_sequences=True, go_backwards=doBackwards)
    h = decoder_lstm(embedded)
    if options.extra is not None:
      for _ in range(options.extra):
        h = LSTM(options.lstm_capacity, return_sequences=True,go_backwards=doBackwards)(h)
  fromhidden = Dense(numwords, activation='linear')
  out = TimeDistributed(fromhidden)(h)
  #tf.keras.Model
  model = Model(input, out,name = How_To_Name_It)
  opt = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(lr=options.lr)
  lss = parsing_loss
  model.compile(opt, lss,metrics = [perplexity])
  model.summary()
  return model



def train_some_text_OR_evaluate(model, text_set, to_evaluate=False):
    if to_evaluate:
        for batch in tqdm(text_set):
            n, l = batch.shape  
            batch_shifted = np.concatenate([np.ones((n, 1)), batch], axis=1) # prepend start symbol
            batch_out = np.concatenate([batch, np.zeros((n, 1))], axis=1)    # append pad symbol 
            results = model.test_on_batch(batch_shifted, batch_out[:, :, None], return_dict=True)
            #return_dict = True : This parameter is a boolean value that controls whether the return value should be a dict containing the metric results.
        return results
    else:
        for epoch in range(options.epochs):
            for batch in tqdm(text_set):
                n, l = batch.shape
                batch_shifted = np.concatenate([np.ones((n, 1)), batch], axis=1)  # prepend start symbol
                batch_out = np.concatenate([batch, np.zeros((n, 1))], axis=1)     # append pad symbol
                model.train_on_batch(batch_shifted, batch_out[:, :, None])

# takes a list of word indexes and converts them back to the original words using an index-to-word mapping
def decode(seq, _i2w = i2w):
    # seq = np.array(seq)
    return ' '.join([_i2w[idx] if idx < len(_i2w) else '<UNK>' for idx in seq])

# get(word,1) if the word is not there -> get 1 that he is <UNK>(needs to check which index he is)
def encode(sentence, _w2i = w2i):
    words = sentence.split()
    return np.array([_w2i.get(word, 2) for word in words])

"""
generate_seq function using the trained model to predict the probability 
distribution of the next word in the sequence, given the current sequence,
and samples a new word from this distribution.
"""
# its just give me an indexs of words that start at seed index or a start point i give that .
def generate_seq_with_prob(model : Model, seed, size, temperature=1.0):# Greedy Text generator 
    ls = seed.shape[0]
    #This code used the first token of an encoded sentence as a seed,
    #and add zeros to the right side of the seed to form the input to the language model in order to generate the rest of the sentence.
    tokens = np.concatenate([seed, np.zeros(size - ls)])
    prob = 1
    for i in range(ls, size):
        probs = model.predict(tokens[None,:])
        # Extract the i-th probability vector and sample an index from it
        #it uses the util.sample_logits() to sample the next token, 
        #while they could also use torch.argmax() to select the token with the highest probability.
        # but not always. becuse we can be stuck with the same word like 'and' over and over so they select randomly between the highest probs..
        next_token = util.sample_logits(probs[0, i-1, :], temperature=temperature)
        prob *= abs(probs[0, i-1, next_token])
        tokens[i] = next_token
    return [int(t) for t in tokens] , prob / options.top_words #A list of integers representing a samples sentence

def generate_sen(model, size, start_from='<START>', temperature=1):
  seed = encode(start_from)
  sequence , theProb = generate_seq_with_prob(model, seed=seed,  size=size, temperature=temperature)
  sentence = decode(sequence)
  return sentence , theProb

def print_generated_sentences_with_probability(all_models, start_from='i love', size=7, temperatures=[0.1, 1, 10],s = ' - '):
    input_qu = input(f'For a printing sentences with the built-in values :\n start_from = {start_from}, size = {size}\n press 1\nfor your own params press 2\n')
    if(int(input_qu) == 2):
      start_from , size = enter_which_sentence_you_want_to_check()
    else:
      print(f'\n\nThe defult start_from : {start_from} and size to calculate is: {size}')
      print(f'\nstart calc..\n')
    for k, v in all_models.items():
      print(f'model name: {k}\n')
      for temperature in temperatures:
          sentence , prob = generate_sen(v, size, start_from=start_from, temperature=temperature)
          print(f'temperature={temperature}: {sentence}, probability={prob}')
      print(f'\n\n{s*30}\n\n')

  return input_string , num_words_toCheck

def print_perplexity_losses(all_models,s = '-',**data):
  for name, model in all_models.items():
    print(f'\n\t{name}\n')
    results = [train_some_text_OR_evaluate(model, data[dataset], to_evaluate=True) for dataset in ['x_train', 'x_valid', 'x_test']]
    for i, res in enumerate(results):
        print(f"\t\n{['train', 'valid', 'test'][i]}: loss={res['loss']:.5f}, perplexity={res['perplexity']:.5f}")
    print(f'\n{s*40}\n')


def predict_next_word(model, word, temperature=1.0):
    # Encode the input word as a sequence of integers
    input_sequence = encode(word)
    # Pass the input sequence through the model to get the probability distribution of the next word
    probs = model.predict(input_sequence[None, :])
    # Sample the next word from the probability distribution
    next_word_index = util.sample_logits(probs[0, -1, :], temperature=temperature)# [0:i] for all the sentnce after
    # Decode the index of the next word to get the actual word
    next_word = decode(next_word_index) # was in []
    return next_word

def predict_next_word(model, word, temperature=10.0):
    # Encode the input word as a sequence of integers
    input_sequence = encode(word)
    # Pass the input sequence through the model to get the probability distribution of the next word
    probs = model.predict(input_sequence[None, :])
    # Sample the next word from the probability distribution
    next_word_index = util.sample_logits(probs[0, -1, :], temperature=temperature)# [0:i] for all the sentnce after
    # Decode the index of the next word to get the actual word
    next_word = decode(next_word_index) # was in []
    return next_word


def UI(model):
  word = input("enter word : ")
  preticted = predict_next_word(model,word)
  print(f'\nWord you entered is : {word}\n\nWord predicted after : {preticted}\n')

def parsing_loss(y_true, y_pred):
    return K.sparse_categorical_crossentropy(y_true, y_pred, from_logits=True)

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
def splitData(text_data):
  train_data, test_data = train_test_split(text_data, test_size=0.2,shuffle=True, random_state=42)
  val_data, test_data = train_test_split(test_data ,test_size=0.5,shuffle=True, random_state=42)
  return train_data , val_data,test_data

def perplexity(y_true, y_pred):
    loss = parsing_loss(y_true, y_pred)
    perplexity = K.exp(loss)
    return perplexity

def My_Sequential(How_To_Name_It,doBackwards=False,doBidirectional=False):
  if((doBackwards == True) and (doBidirectional == True)):
    print("we want only 1 choise of back learner")
    return 
  input = Input(shape=(None, ))
  embedding = Embedding(numwords, options.embedding_size, input_length=None)
  embedded = embedding(input)
  
  if(doBidirectional == True):
    decoder_lstm = Bidirectional(LSTM(options.lstm_capacity, return_sequences=True))
    h = decoder_lstm(embedded)
    if options.extra is not None:
      for _ in range(options.extra):
        h = Bidirectional(LSTM(options.lstm_capacity, return_sequences=True))(h)
  else:
    decoder_lstm = LSTM(options.lstm_capacity, return_sequences=True, go_backwards=doBackwards)
    h = decoder_lstm(embedded)
    if options.extra is not None:
      for _ in range(options.extra):
        h = LSTM(options.lstm_capacity, return_sequences=True,go_backwards=doBackwards)(h)
  fromhidden = Dense(numwords, activation='linear')
  out = TimeDistributed(fromhidden)(h)
  model = Model(input, out,name = How_To_Name_It)
  opt = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(lr=options.lr)
  lss = parsing_loss
  model.compile(opt, lss,metrics = [perplexity])
  model.summary()
  return model



def train_some_text_OR_evaluate(model, text_set, to_evaluate=False):
    if to_evaluate:
        for batch in tqdm(text_set):
            n, l = batch.shape  
            batch_shifted = np.concatenate([np.ones((n, 1)), batch], axis=1) 
            batch_out = np.concatenate([batch, np.zeros((n, 1))], axis=1)   
            results = model.test_on_batch(batch_shifted, batch_out[:, :, None], return_dict=True)
          
        return results
    else:
        for epoch in range(options.epochs):
            for batch in tqdm(text_set):
                n, l = batch.shape
                batch_shifted = np.concatenate([np.ones((n, 1)), batch], axis=1)  
                batch_out = np.concatenate([batch, np.zeros((n, 1))], axis=1)   
                model.train_on_batch(batch_shifted, batch_out[:, :, None])

def decode(seq, _i2w = i2w):
    return ' '.join([_i2w[idx] if idx < len(_i2w) else '<UNK>' for idx in seq])

def encode(sentence, _w2i = w2i):
    words = sentence.split()
    return np.array([_w2i.get(word, 2) for word in words])

def generate_seq_with_prob(model : Model, seed, size, temperature=1.0):
    ls = seed.shape[0]
    tokens = np.concatenate([seed, np.zeros(size - ls)])
    prob = 1
    for i in range(ls, size):
        probs = model.predict(tokens[None,:])
        next_token = util.sample_logits(probs[0, i-1, :], temperature=temperature)
        prob *= abs(probs[0, i-1, next_token])
        tokens[i] = next_token
    return [int(t) for t in tokens] , prob / options.top_words 

def generate_sen(model, size, start_from='<START>', temperature=1):
  seed = encode(start_from)
  sequence , theProb = generate_seq_with_prob(model, seed=seed,  size=size, temperature=temperature)
  sentence = decode(sequence)
  return sentence , theProb


def print_generated_sentences_with_probability(all_models, start_from='i love', size=7, temperatures=[0.1, 1, 10],s = ' - '):
    input_qu = input(f'For a printing sentences with the built-in values :\n start_from = {start_from}, size = {size}\n press 1\nfor your own params press 2\n')
    if(input_qu == 2):
      start_from , size = enter_which_sentence_you_want_to_check()
    for k, v in all_models.items():
      print(f'model name: {k}\n')
      for temperature in temperatures:
          sentence , prob = generate_sen(v, size, start_from=start_from, temperature=temperature)
          print(f'temperature={temperature}: {sentence}, probability={prob}')
      print(f'\n\n{s*30}\n\n')


def enter_which_sentence_you_want_to_check():
  input_string = input("Please enter some text to check sentences with it and probabilitys: ")
  input_size = input("Do you want the size to be the same as the number of words you entered or more? (yes/no)")
  if input_size.lower() == 'yes':
    word_list = input_string.split()
    num_words_toCheck = len(word_list)
  else:
    num_words_toCheck = input("Enter the number of words you want to calculate: ")
    word_list = input_string.split()[:int(num_words_toCheck)]
  num_words_in_input = len(word_list)
  print(f'\n\nThe number of words in your input is: {num_words_in_input} and size to calculate is: {num_words_toCheck}')
  print(f'\nstart calc..\n')
  return input_string , num_words_toCheck

def print_perplexity_losses(all_models,s = '-',**data):
  for name, model in all_models.items():
    print(f'\n\t{name}\n')
    results = [train_some_text_OR_evaluate(model, data[dataset], to_evaluate=True) for dataset in ['x_train', 'x_valid', 'x_test']]
    for i, res in enumerate(results):
        print(f"\t\n{['train', 'valid', 'test'][i]}: loss={res['loss']:.5f}, perplexity={res['perplexity']:.5f}")
    print(f'\n{s*40}\n')


def predict_next_word(model, word, temperature=1.0):
    input_sequence = encode(word)
    probs = model.predict(input_sequence[None, :])
    next_word_index = util.sample_logits(probs[0, -1, :], temperature=temperature)
    next_word = decode(next_word_index)
    return next_word
